    2026-05-19T16:55:00Z)

(Correction
    "Report filenames name the report's subject, not its conversational ancestry. Names like `response-to-...`, `review-of-...`, or `audit-of-...` are poor durable locators when they hide the actual topic behind another report number. The file path should tell a future agent what the report is about without opening a chain of prior reports."
    "> 229-response-to-oa-154-primary-hrhz-audit.md

We need to forbid this type of report name. So find out what the report is about and give it a proper name. Do you understand why I don't want this type of name for a report file name?"
    "Correcting a report filename whose locator described that it responded to OA/154 instead of naming its actual persona-orchestrate subject."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T17:05:00Z)

(Constraint
    "Never delete an uncommitted report. Commit first, then delete. Deletion of a committed report only removes it from the work tree — git history retains the substance. Deletion of an uncommitted report is total loss. This applies to the rename/amalgamation protocol: when a new report absorbs a predecessor, the predecessor's deletion is safe ONLY after both reports are committed."
    "reports always have to be committed so that the deletions mean the report is lost. It just means now it's in the commit history and not the work tree. So don't ever delete a report that hasn't been committed, obviously."
    "Adding a safety constraint to the rename/amalgamation protocol. The git-history-holds-lineage assumption only works when content has actually landed in git."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T17:00:00Z)

(Constraint
    "Report-naming discipline must hit disk as a skill — not just in the intent log. Intent records the psyche's statements; rules that govern agent behavior live in skills/. Report naming (filename convention, -v2/v3 suffix for iteration, supersession via write-new-delete-old-same-commit, commit-before-delete) is the basic naming discipline every agent needs, separate from the larger skills/reporting.md (chat-vs-report, inline-summary, visuals, soft caps)."
    "by enforced, I meant like, is it in the agent guideline files? … if it's just in the intent, then the intent hasn't hit the disk. … translate that to, it's pretty basic stuff. So we need a reporting instruction that isn't big that all agents can read, where they don't necessarily need to make diagrams and things like that. They need to understand how the naming works, the report naming. So this isn't like advanced reporting skill. This is very basic naming skill, so it needs to go somewhere, hit the disk outside of the intent."
    "Adding the disk-not-just-intent enforcement principle for behavior-governing rules, and the basic-naming-as-its-own-skill split (separate from advanced reporting)."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T17:30:00Z)

(Constraint
    "Report sweeps should remove stale reports from the work tree after their useful substance is committed into fresh, topic-focused reports. Reports that cover too many topics are poor handoff objects; each fresh report should be scoped by topic so another agent can use the path directly."
    "do a report sweep, like any old reports you have with stale stuff. If there's nothing good in them, delete them. If there's anything good, move all of the good stuff into a new fresh report. By topic, obviously. I don't want reports that cover too many topics. They're not very useful for handing over to other agents."
    "Direction before resuming Horizon redesign work: clean stale report inventory first, preserve good substance only in focused handoff reports, and delete obsolete reports after the preserved material is committed."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T12:26:44Z)

(Correction
    "When you'd say 'ready to close', 'ready to merge', 'ready to ship' or similar bureaucratic workflow-state phrasing in chat, either do the action yourself (close the bead, merge the branch) or ask a specific question naming the choice. 'Ready to X' without action and without a clarifying question is empty noise — it leaves the psyche guessing whether you're reporting status, asking permission, or asking them to do the action themselves. When the phrasing combines with a bare opaque identifier (bead UID without inline description) the indirection compounds and tells the psyche nothing at all."
    "saying bead primary HJ63 is ready to close doesn't fucking tell me anything about what you mean, because I have no fucking idea what HJ63 the fuck is. … Are you asking me if you should close a bead that should be closed? Are you asking me if you should implement it? … if it's supposed to be closed, you should close it. If you're asking me if you should implement it, then that's a different question."
    "Correcting my chat reply 'Bead primary-hj63 is ready to close' that combined two indirections — bureaucratic workflow language and bare opaque identifier — even though AGENTS.md opaque-identifiers-in-chat hard override and the bureaucratic-noise correction in workspace.nota each already forbid one of them. This sharpens to a positive rule: actions are taken, not announced as 'ready'."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19 18:30)

